07713nam a22009375i 9780824860967DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20112011hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248609677 a10.1515/97808248609672doi  a(DE-B1597)483748  a(OCoLC)1024036811  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aHM1126 -- M438 2011eb 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a303.6/909500aMediating Across Difference :bOceanic and Asian Approaches to Conflict Resolution /ced. by Roland Bleiker, Morgan J. Brigg. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (264 p.) :b2 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aWriting Past Colonialism00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tI. The Values and Limits of Western Approaches to Conflict Resolution -- tChapter 1. Postcolonial Conflict Resolution -- tChapter 2. Silence in Western Models of Conflict Resolution -- tChapter 3. Local Conflict Resolution in the Shadows of Liberal International Peacebuilding -- tII. Australian Aboriginal and Māori Approaches to Conflict Resolution -- tChapter 4. Conflict Murri Way: Managing through Place and Relatedness -- tChapter 5. Conflict Resolution and Decolonisation: Aboriginal Australian Case Studies in ‘Enlarged Thinking’ -- tChapter 6. Māori Dispute Resolution: Traditional Conceptual Regulators and Contemporary Processes -- tIII. Melanesian Approaches to Conflict Resolution -- tChapter 7. Christianity, Custom, and Law: Conflict and Peacemaking in the Postconflict Solomon Islands -- tChapter 8. Bougainville: A Source of Inspiration for Conflict Resolution -- tIV. East Asian Approaches to Conflict Resolution -- tChapter 9. Crossing Borders: Indonesian Experience with Local Conflict Resolution -- tChapter 10. Mediating Difference in Uchi Space: Conflict Management Lessons from Japan -- tChapter 11. Shu and the Chinese Quest for Harmony: A Confucian Approach to Mediating across Difference -- tChapter 12. Korean Sources of Conflict Resolution: An Inquiry into the Concept of Han -- tChapter 13. Conclusion: Mediating the Mediation with Difference -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMediating Across Difference is based on a fundamental premise: to deal adequately with conflict—and particularly with conflict stemming from cultural and other differences—requires genuine openness to different cultural practices and dialogue between different ways of knowing and being. Equally essential is a shift away from understanding cultural difference as an inevitable source of conflict, and the development of a more critical attitude toward previously under-examined Western assumptions about conflict and its resolution.To address the ensuing challenges, this book introduces and explores some of the rich insights into conflict resolution emanating from Asia and Oceania. Although often overlooked, these local traditions offer a range of useful ways of thinking about and dealing with difference and conflict in a globalizing world. To bring these traditions into exchange with mainstream Western conflict resolution, the editors present the results of collaborative work between experienced scholars and culturally knowledgeable practitioners from numerous parts of Asia and Oceania. The result is a series of interventions that challenge conventional Western notions of conflict resolution and provide academics, policy makers, diplomats, mediators, and local conflict workers with new possibilities to approach, prevent, and resolve conflict.Contributors: Roland Bleiker; Volker Boege; Morgan Brigg; Stephen Chan; Frans de Jalong, Sr.; Lorraine Garasu; Mary Graham; Hoang Young-ju; Carwyn Jones; Joy Kere; Debra McDougall; Norifumi Namatame; Chengxin Pan; Oliver Richmond; Deborah Bird Rose; Muhadi Sugiono; Tarja Väyrynen; Polly O. Walker; Jacqueline Wasilewski.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aBleiker, Roland, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBleiker, Roland, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBoege, Volker, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrigg, Morgan J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBrigg, Morgan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChan, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarasu, Lorraine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGraham, Mary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJalong, Frans de, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, Carwyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKere, Joy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcDougall, Debra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNamatame, Norifumi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPan, Chengxin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRichmond, Oliver P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRose, Deborah Bird, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSugiono, Muhadi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVäyrynen, Tarja, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWalker, Polly O., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWasilewski, Jacqueline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aYoung-ju, Hoang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov